                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Chieftain's Museum, Rome, Georgia</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/3C7E670B-1DD8-B71B-0B25C5CD76BF4A04.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="large white house, green lawn, two trees in front" title="The museum tells the story of Major Ridge, the influential Ridge family including prominent son John Ridge, Cherokee history, and the Trail of Tears, as well as subsequent history of the home and region." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>The museum tells the story of Major Ridge, the influential Ridge family including prominent son John Ridge, Cherokee history, and the Trail of Tears, as well as subsequent history of the home and region.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Brown's Ferry Tavern, Chattanooga, Tennessee</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/3C7E6990-1DD8-B71B-0B75FFAF17A4B2A8.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="structure in the background with large chimney on the end; signs saying Brown's Ferry Tavern" title="Cherokee leader John Brown, who owned 640 acres in this area, ordered the construction of Browns Ferry Tavern in 1803. In 1838, the road running past this structure was the route by which several Cherokee detachments were removed to present-day Oklahoma." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>Cherokee leader John Brown, who owned 640 acres in this area, ordered the construction of Browns Ferry Tavern in 1803. In 1838, the road running past this structure was the route by which several Cherokee detachments were removed to present-day Oklahoma.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Mantle Rock Preserve, Joy, Kentucky</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/3C7E6AE0-1DD8-B71B-0BD3C7623B4A0272.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="sunlight coming through trees with green leaves" title="Thousands of Cherokee camped for weeks along the main (northern) route, near Mantle Rock, during the winter of 1838-39 as they waited for ice conditions in the Ohio River to allow a safe crossing." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>Thousands of Cherokee camped for weeks along the main (northern) route, near Mantle Rock, during the winter of 1838-39 as they waited for ice conditions in the Ohio River to allow a safe crossing.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Cherokee Retracement at Pea Ridge National Military Park, Garfield, Arkansas</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/3C7E6C3A-1DD8-B71B-0B1C7619213A627A.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="dozens of people walk a section of the Trail of Tears, winter scene, trees with no leaves" title="The Pea Ridge National Military Park encompasses 4,300 acres and features a visitor center, museum, self-guided tours, reconstructed Elkhorn Tavern, and a retracement trail along a 2.5-mile original route segment of the Trail of Tears." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>The Pea Ridge National Military Park encompasses 4,300 acres and features a visitor center, museum, self-guided tours, reconstructed Elkhorn Tavern, and a retracement trail along a 2.5-mile original route segment of the Trail of Tears.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
